<p><strong>MEDIA RELEASE</strong></p>
<p><strong>Guam, Thursday 11 March 2021</strong></p>
<p>OneQode is thrilled to announce that its <a href="/about/guam/">Gaming Hub in Guam</a> is now open for business, offering a brand-new latency-neutral game server location in the heart of Asia-Pacific.</p>
<p>For the very first time, gamers in the APAC region have a level playing field for international gaming, with the Guam Hub connected to the surrounding nations at low latency via high-capacity undersea fibre.</p>
<p>Thanks to the Hub, game publishers, developers, and server providers have access to dedicated server capacity and co-location facilities on the unique island of Guam.</p>
<h2>Guam: a solution to the inter-regional gameplay problem</h2>
<p>Gaming in Asia-Pacific has long been at the mercy of latency. Gamers have been forced to either play local on hyper-regionalised servers or put up with a jittery international experience.</p>
<p>The issue is predominantly geographical. Because of the dispersed nature of the population and the complexities of subsea networks, the challenge for many server providers has been locating a neutral ‘hub’ location which ticks all the boxes to serve the massive regional population.</p>
<p>OneQode, the first provider to operate on the <a href="/media/oneqode-fastest-path-to-asia/">fastest submarine fibre cable to Asia</a> from Australia's east coast, built the Guam Gaming Hub on the US territory of Guam to provide low-latency game servers for the regions gamers.</p>
<p>From Guam, OneQode's international network can reach between 3 and 5 billion people with under 100ms of latency - the sweet spot for most online games.</p>
