<p>Because the Hub is roughly equidistant from surrounding nations, players can now meet on the same digital terms - whether they're located in China, Japan, India or Australia.</p>
<p>For Ben Cooper, Chief Product Officer at OneQode, this has been a long time coming:</p>
<blockquote>
	<p>“I began to work on the Guam hub concept in 2016. The goal was to find a place with the best latency to as many people as possible. Much easier said than done - but thanks to the team alongside me at OneQode, our carrier partners and RTI, Guam is finally ready to act as a gaming hub. We’re really excited to share this with the world and change gaming in the Asia-Pacific region, for good.”</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>A latency optimised network</h2>
<p>OneQode's Gaming Hub is the culmination of a major international deployment and plugs directly into a backbone purpose-built to provide a premium, low-latency experience across the board. Boasting several core routing locations throughout Asia-Pacific, the OneQode network is fed by high-capacity submarine links and integrates with many of the largest local providers in each location.</p>
<p>By making a concerted effort to get as close to end-users as possible, the network prioritises user experience over lowest-cost paths. It also leverages OneQode's proprietary, software-defined core routing equipment and heavy-duty DDoS filters and scrubbers, providing resiliency and reliability.</p>
<p>The result? Accessible, latency-focused services on a network obsessively built to get packets where they need to go as quickly (and securely) as possible.</p>
<h2>Benefits for developers and publishers</h2>
<p>For those looking to take advantage of the Gaming Hub opportunity, the benefits are significant. Developers and publishers can solve their server population issue by removing the need for large amounts of regional gaming servers. Instead, operators can now headquarter their operations in the Hub and allow the approximately 1.5B gamers in APAC to connect in one homogenised location. </p>
